            "description": "### Get a specific recipe\n\nRetrieve the details of a single recipe.\n\n**Method:** `GET`  \n**Endpoint:** `{{base_url}}/api/recipes/1?id=1`\n\n---\n\n#### URL structure\n\n- `{{base_url}}` – Workspace variable that stores the base URL of your API (for example: `https://miam.example.com`).\n    \n- Path: `/api/recipes/1`\n    \n    - `1` is the ID of the recipe in the path.\n        \n- Query parameters:\n    \n    - `id` (required in this example): `1` – recipe ID passed as a query parameter.\n        \n\nSo the full request will look like this once `{{base_url}}` is resolved, e.g.:\n\n\\`\\`\\`http  \nGET [https://your-domain.com/api/recipes/1?id=1](https://your-domain.com/api/recipes/1?id=1)\n\nStartFragment\n\n#### Expected behavior\n\n- **200 OK** – Returns the recipe details as JSON (for example: title, ingredients, preparation steps).\n    \n- **4xx errors** – Returned if the recipe does not exist, the ID is invalid, or the request is malformed.\n    \n- **5xx errors** – Returned if the server encounters an internal error.\n    \n\nStartFragment\n\n#### Notes\n\n- Make sure the `{{base_url}}` variable is defined in your active environment (e.g. `https://localhost:3000` during development).\n    \n- You can change the recipe ID by editing both:\n    \n    - the path segment (`/api/recipes/{id}`), and\n        \n    - the `id` query parameter."
          },
          "response": []
